Back in April 2022, Warner Bros. Discovery came into the world
with a slew of near-existential disadvantages=E2=80=94the company was burde=
ned by a $55 billion debt load, a BBB credit rating, and a rocky operating =
environment for its array of linear TV offerings, cable channels, and Holly=
wood fare. The equity markets didn=E2=80=99t look kindly upon the Frankenmo=
nster that David Zaslav had created through the combination of Discovery Co=
mmunications, his challenged cable TV business, and the vestiges of AT&T=E2=
=80=99s Warner Media. Since the company=E2=80=99s formation, the
stock is down 55 percent. The S&P 500 has risen 20 percent during the same =
time period.

=C2=A0

And yet if WBD=E2=80=99s fourth quarter 2024 performance is a harbinger of =
things to come, the worst may be over. I=E2=80=99ve long argued that WBD is=
 really a publicly traded leveraged buyout, and the key to unlocking value =
was the simultaneous reduction of its debt=E2=80=94an objective that Zaz ha=
s been highly rewarded to achieve=E2=80=94in
combination with the hoped-for growth of its direct-to-consumer business an=
d an increase in overall profitability. At some point, I=E2=80=99ve contend=
ed, the company would pay down enough debt and make enough free cash flow (=
and project the ability to rev it up on both fronts) that investors would l=
ook past the ominous headlines about its declining linear TV assets, its fo=
rfeiture of the rights to televise the NBA, and the vicissitudes of its fil=
m division.

It looks like
we=E2=80=99ve now reached an inflection point for the company. Net debt at =
WBD is $34.6 billion=E2=80=94$40 billion of gross debt, less $5.4 billion o=
f cash and cash equivalents=E2=80=94and the company=E2=80=99s leverage rati=
o of 3.8x adjusted EBITDA is on its way down, or so management hopes, to a =
ratio of 2.5x-3x gross leverage. Meanwhile, Max is growing, and Zaz has sig=
naled that he=E2=80=99s willing to kill his little darlings at Discovery, i=
f it comes to that. =E2=80=9CD.T.C. net adds and EBITDA continue to shine,=
=E2=80=9D Kutgun
Maral, at Evercore ISI, wrote in a quick note after the earnings release on=
 Thursday.

The $3 Billion Improvement
--------------------------

WBD has paid down $19 billion of its debt load in nearly three
years. =E2=80=9CWe will continue to be super, super focused on this,=E2=80=
=9D C.F.O. Gunnar Wiedenfels said during the company=E2=80=99s earnings cal=
l on Thursday morning. As I=E2=80=99ve reported before, the tenor of the WB=
D debt is also quite advantageous to the company, at least in the current i=
nterest-rate environment. At the end of December, the average maturity of t=
he company=E2=80=99s remaining debt was 13.4 years, at an average interest =
rate cost of 4.7 percent. That=E2=80=99s tasty for a company with a BBB cre=
dit
rating, considering the yield on the 10-year Treasury is currently 4.2 perc=
ent.

=C2=A0

WBD does have some near-term debt maturities, including $2.2 billion due th=
is month, which explains the company=E2=80=99s logic for carrying $5.4 bill=
ion in cash on its balance sheet. On the earnings call, Gunnar said the bal=
ance sheet is in =E2=80=9Cvery good shape now=E2=80=9D and that he is not w=
orried about any near-term debt maturities. =E2=80=9CI view our capital
structure as a real asset,=E2=80=9D he said. I don=E2=80=99t know when, or =
if, the credit rating agencies will upgrade WBD=E2=80=99s BBB credit rating=
=2E But when they do=E2=80=94and it shou=
ld be soon(ish), I would think=E2=80=
=94that will be the day the rocket fuel gets injected into the WBD publicly=
 traded L.B.O. (This is not investment advice.)

