ess. Zaz=E2=80=99s strategy of internationalizing HBO/Max, WBD=E2=80=99s di=
rect-to-consumer offering, seems to be paying off. Total D.T.C. subscribers=
 reached 117 million in the fourth quarter, with the majority of those subs=
cribers, nearly 60 million, coming from outside the United States. After pe=
netrating Latin America, the service will soon light up in the U.K., Irelan=
d, Australia, Germany, and Italy. =E2=80=9CMax became one of the very few
global scaled and profitable streaming services,=E2=80=9D the company wrote=
 in a letter to shareholders that accompanied the earnings report.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

There was also unexpected subscriber growth in the U.S., with some 4.5 mill=
ion new subscribers domestically, as compared to analysts=E2=80=99 expectat=
ions of 2.8 million. =E2=80=9CThe U.S. is a pretty mature market,=E2=80=9D =
Zaz said. =E2=80=9CWe think that there=E2=80=99s still some growth, given t=
he
quality of our service, and we=E2=80=99re fighting for that.=E2=80=9D Meanw=
hile, streaming is now solidly profitable at WBD. In the fourth quarter, D.=
T.C. adjusted EBITDA=E2=80=94I hate that term, as Zaz knows=E2=80=94was $40=
9 million, up from a loss in the fourth quarter of 2023 and above the $275 =
million that Wall Street was expecting, as Maral wrote in his note. For all=
 of 2024, D.T.C.=E2=80=99s adjusted EBITDA was $677 million, up exponential=
ly from $103 million in 2023.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Zaz wasn=E2=80=99t shy about touting the success of this division. =E2=80=
=9COur direct-to-consumer business contributed almost $700 million in EBITD=
A, a $3 billion improvement in just two years,=E2=80=9D he said on the call=
=2E =E2=80=9CAnd we expect direct-to-consu=
mer EBITDA to nearly double in 2025=
=2E=E2=80=9D He specifically cited the suc=
cess globally of The White Lotus, H=
ouse of the Dragon, and The Pitt as =E2=80=9Ccompelling,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9C=
quality,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Coriginal storytelling.=E2=80=9D
(The Pitt, of course, is not without its legal headaches, as my partner Eri=
q Gardner can assure you ( https://puck.news/is-hbo-max-the-pitt-just-er-wi=
th-a-new-title/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&u=
tm_content=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_=
action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).) Maral wro=
te in a subsequent note on Friday that WBD=E2=80=99s D.T.C. =E2=80=9Ctrends=
=E2=80=9D remain =E2=80=9Chighly encouraging,=E2=80=9D with subscribers gro=
wing to =E2=80=9Cover=E2=80=9D 150 million by the end of next year and EBIT=
DA =E2=80=9Cnearly=E2=80=9D doubling to $1.3 billion this year.

The other happy story in the fourth quarter results came in WBD=E2=80=99s s=
tudio segment. The company reported that the television production business=
 manufactured 80 shows for both WBD and other streamers and broadcast netwo=
rks, and was the top supplier of live-action TV to WBD and to others. Zaz h=
ighlighted hits such as The Penguin, =E2=80=9Cone of the top three most vie=
wed original debut seasons on Max ever,=E2=80=9D and Presumed Innocent, a b=
ig hit for Apple TV. In the fourth
quarter, WBD=E2=80=99s studio segment generated revenue of nearly $3.7 bill=
ion, up 16 percent year over year, and adjusted EBITDA=E2=80=94kills me eve=
ry time=E2=80=94of $950 million, up a whopping 75 percent year over year. Z=
az is especially jazzed about the debut of Warner Bros.=E2=80=99 Superman f=
ilm in July. (Superman, alas, is also not without some legal issues ( https=
://puck.news/new-superman-could-be-barred-from-release-outside-u-s/?utm_cam=
paign=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Varsit=
y+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcus=
tomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), as Eriq
can also remind you=E2=80=A6)

The Cable Quagmire
------------------

WBD=E2=80=99s linear TV offerings are still struggling, of course, no
matter how creatively Robert Gibbs, the new WBD head of communications, is =
trying to apply lipstick to the pig. And, critically, this segment of WBD=
=E2=80=99s business is still generating the bulk of the company=E2=80=99s a=
djusted EBITDA. In 2024, the networks segment generated adjusted EBITDA of =
$8.1 billion, down 10 percent from the $9 billion in 2023. The trend lines =
are even worse: In the fourth quarter, adjusted EBITDA was $1.9 billion, do=
wn 13 percent from $2.2 billion
from the year earlier quarter. =E2=80=9CThe earnings generated by our linea=
r networks continue to support our ability to invest in our transformation,=
=E2=80=9D the company wrote to shareholders. You=E2=80=99ve got to hand it =
to Gibbs for his spin capabilities.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

That, of course, is why Zaz recently reorged WBD to make it easier to poten=
tially spin off CNN, TNT, the Food Network, and other declining cable asset=
s into their own
publicly traded company, or possibly gin up some future merger with Comcast=
=E2=80=99s SpinCo. My sense, particularly based on the signals that he sent=
 Thursday, is that he=E2=80=99s getting close to pulling the trigger here. =
=E2=80=9CThis new structure will provide investors with better visibility t=
o the strength of our streaming and studios business and will give us real =
strategic value and optionality into the future,=E2=80=9D Zaz told the Wall=
 Street analysts. When BofA=E2=80=99s Jessica Reif Ehrlich asked about
future strategic initiatives, Zaz replied that the company=E2=80=99s new st=
ructure allowed it to be =E2=80=9Cbetter able to respond to this generation=
al disruption=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccreate potential opportunities to unloc=
k additional shareholder value, which we=E2=80=99re focused on.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Zaz tried to provide some hopium for the folks at CNN by citing the coming =
subscription and digital offerings being designed by Mark Thompson
and Alex MacCallum, who =E2=80=9Cbuilt the digital business at The New York=
 Times.=E2=80=9D But that=E2=80=99s still going to be a long putt. The WBD =
C.E.O. garnered perhaps the most attention for what he said about the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s sports agenda. (My partner John Ourand has done terrific repor=
ting on this, of course.)=C2=A0

Our friend Rich Greenfield at LightShed Partners asked Zaz about the WBD sp=
orts strategy these days. He replied
that his team is =E2=80=9Cdisciplined=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Copportunistic=
=E2=80=9D when it comes to the sports rights opportunities and that WBD is =
=E2=80=9Cmoney good=E2=80=9D on almost all of its current sports offerings:=
 =E2=80=9CWe don=E2=80=99t need any more sports anywhere in the world in or=
der to support our business.=E2=80=9D Gunnar added that =E2=80=9Cseveral hu=
ndred million=E2=80=9D dollars of expenses related to sports will be elimin=
ated in 2026, along with some associated ad revenue, of course. =E2=80=9CBu=
t this should certainly be a few hundred million dollar improvement in
2026 over 2025,=E2=80=9D he said.

A Zaz Ending?
-------------

Where WBD goes from here is anyone=E2=80=99s guess, of course. Investor
sentiment seems to be changing for the better. In the past six months, the =
stock is up 51 percent. But it=E2=80=99s also down the aforementioned 55 pe=
rcent since the company was formed nearly three years ago. Is the glass hal=
f empty or half full?=C2=A0

That=E2=80=99s one of the most intriguing parlor games being played in Holl=
ywood and on Wall Street these days. Zaz, of course, remains supremely opti=
mistic. =E2=80=9CWe really believe that the global players will be those th=
at will really
prosper in the years ahead, and ultimately be the largest sustainable growt=
h media companies,=E2=80=9D he told of analyst Kannan Venkateshwar on the e=
arnings call. =E2=80=9CThere will probably be four, or five, or six, and ou=
r job every day is to fight to get a seat at that table.=E2=80=9D The fourt=
h quarter results, if they can be sustained, at least indicate that Zaz and=
 WBD will likely be one of the =E2=80=9Cfour, five, or six.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=8A

From the Cheap Seats
--------------------

On the demise of the Super League in Europe: =E2=80=9CThe creators
of the Super League underestimated how strong fans would unite against a sy=
stem that eradicated meritocracy. It makes me think the only way to stop mu=
ltiple automatic qualifiers for the future College Football Playoffs is if =
fans unite. It seems the only thing stopping Greg Sankey and Tony Petitti i=
s a public protest at the Big Ten and SEC conference basketball tournaments=
=2E I wish my fellow Big Ten brethren,=20=
and our SEC peers, had the courage to=20=
mount a similar
protest as the Europeans did to halt the Super League.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A =
Varsity subscriber

=C2=A0

On IndyCar drivers: =E2=80=9CIn your Q&A with Shanks, you mixed up Alex Pal=
ou with Alex Bowman. Alex Palou is an IndyCar driver. Alex Bowman is a NASC=
AR driver.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A sports media veteran

=C2=A0

[Ed note: No dinner tonight, Marchand!]

On the donnybrook in a Starbucks between NFL Media=E2=80=99s Ian Rapoport a=
nd Fox=E2=80=99s Jordan Schultz, son of former Starbucks C.E.O. Howard Schu=
ltz: =E2=80=9CDoes Jordan pay at Starbucks?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A Varsity sub=
scriber asking the right question

=E2=80=8A

Until Thursday,

John

