px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Back in April 2022, Warner Bros. Discovery=
 came into the world
with a slew of near-existential disadvantages=E2=80=94the company was burde=
ned by a $55 billion debt load, a BBB credit rating, and a rocky operating =
environment for its array of linear TV offerings, cable channels, and Holly=
wood fare. The equity markets didn=E2=80=99t look kindly upon the Frankenmo=
nster that <strong>David Zaslav </strong>had created through the combinatio=
n of Discovery Communications, his challenged cable TV business, and the ve=
stiges of AT&amp;T=E2=80=99s Warner Media. Since the company=E2=80=99s form=
ation, the
stock is down 55 percent. The S&amp;P 500 has risen 20 percent during the s=
ame time period.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">And yet if WBD=E2=80=99s fourth quarte=
r 2024 performance is a harbinger of things to come, the worst may be over.=
 I=E2=80=99ve long argued that WBD is really a publicly traded leveraged bu=
yout, and the key to unlocking value was the simultaneous reduction of its =
debt=E2=80=94an objective that Zaz has been <em>highly </em>rewarded to ach=
ieve=E2=80=94in
combination with the hoped-for growth of its direct-to-consumer business an=
d an increase in overall profitability. At some point, I=E2=80=99ve contend=
ed, the company would pay down enough debt and make enough free cash flow (=
and project the ability to rev it up on both fronts) that investors would l=
ook past the ominous headlines about its declining linear TV assets, its fo=
rfeiture of the rights to televise the NBA, and the vicissitudes of its fil=
m division.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>It looks like
we=E2=80=99ve now reached an inflection point for the company. Net debt at =
WBD is $34.6 billion=E2=80=94$40 billion of gross debt, less $5.4 billion o=
f cash and cash equivalents=E2=80=94and the company=E2=80=99s leverage rati=
o of 3.8x adjusted EBITDA is on its way down, or so management hopes, to a =
ratio of 2.5x-3x gross leverage. Meanwhile, Max is growing, and Zaz has sig=
naled that he=E2=80=99s willing to kill his little darlings at Discovery, i=
f it comes to that. =E2=80=9CD.T.C. net adds and EBITDA continue to shine,=
=E2=80=9D <strong>Kutgun
Maral</strong>, at Evercore ISI, wrote in a quick note after the earnings r=
elease on Thursday.</p></div>
