ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">WBD has paid down $19 billion of its debt load =
in nearly three
years. =E2=80=9CWe will continue to be super, super focused on this,=E2=80=
=9D C.F.O. <strong>Gunnar Wiedenfels</strong> said during the company=E2=80=
=99s earnings call on Thursday morning. As I=E2=80=99ve reported before, th=
e tenor of the WBD debt is also quite advantageous to the company, at least=
 in the current interest-rate environment. At the end of December, the aver=
age maturity of the company=E2=80=99s remaining debt was 13.4 years, at an =
average interest rate cost of 4.7 percent. That=E2=80=99s tasty for a compa=
ny with a BBB credit
rating, considering the yield on the 10-year Treasury is currently 4.2 perc=
ent.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;">WBD does have some near-term debt maturities, including $2.2 billion=
 due this month, which explains the company=E2=80=99s logic for carrying $5=
=2E4 billion in cash on its balance she=
et. On the earnings call, Gunnar said=20=
the balance sheet is in =E2=80=9Cvery good shape now=E2=80=9D and that he i=
s not worried about any near-term debt maturities. =E2=80=9CI view our capi=
tal
structure as a real asset,=E2=80=9D he said. I don=E2=80=99t know when, or =
if, the credit rating agencies will upgrade WBD=E2=80=99s BBB credit rating=
=2E But when they do=E2=80=94and it shou=
ld be soon(ish), I would think=E2=80=
=94that will be the day the rocket fuel gets injected into the WBD publicly=
 traded L.B.O. (This is not investment advice.)</p></div>
