line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">WBD=E2=80=99s linear TV offerings are still str=
uggling, of course, no
matter how creatively <strong>Robert Gibbs</strong>, the new WBD head of co=
mmunications, is trying to apply lipstick to the pig. And, critically, this=
 segment of WBD=E2=80=99s business is <em>still </em>generating the bulk of=
 the company=E2=80=99s adjusted EBITDA. In 2024, the networks segment gener=
ated adjusted EBITDA of $8.1 billion, down 10 percent from the $9 billion i=
n 2023. The trend lines are even worse: In the fourth quarter, adjusted EBI=
TDA was $1.9 billion, down <em>13 percent</em> from $2.2 billion
from the year earlier quarter. =E2=80=9CThe earnings generated by our linea=
r networks continue to support our ability to invest in our transformation,=
=E2=80=9D the company wrote to shareholders. You=E2=80=99ve got to hand it =
to Gibbs for his spin capabilities.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">That, of cour=
se, is why Zaz recently reorged WBD to make it easier to potentially spin o=
ff CNN, TNT, the Food Network, and other declining cable assets into their =
own
publicly traded company, or possibly gin up some future merger with Comcast=
=E2=80=99s SpinCo. My sense, particularly based on the signals that he sent=
 Thursday, is that he=E2=80=99s getting close to pulling the trigger here. =
=E2=80=9CThis new structure will provide investors with better visibility t=
o the strength of our streaming and studios business and will give us real =
strategic value and optionality into the future,=E2=80=9D Zaz told the Wall=
 Street analysts. When BofA=E2=80=99s <strong>Jessica Reif Ehrlich</strong>=
 asked about
future strategic initiatives, Zaz replied that the company=E2=80=99s new st=
ructure allowed it to be =E2=80=9Cbetter able to respond to this generation=
al disruption=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccreate potential opportunities to unloc=
k additional shareholder value, which we=E2=80=99re focused on.=E2=80=9D</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">Zaz tried to provide some hopium for the folks at CNN by =
citing the coming subscription and digital offerings being designed by <str=
ong>Mark Thompson</strong>
and <strong>Alex MacCallum</strong>, who =E2=80=9Cbuilt the digital busines=
s at <em>The New York Times</em>.=E2=80=9D But that=E2=80=99s still going t=
o be a long putt. The WBD C.E.O. garnered perhaps the most attention for wh=
at he said about the company=E2=80=99s sports agenda. (My partner <strong>J=
ohn Ourand</strong> has done terrific reporting on this, of course.)=C2=A0<=
/p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Our friend <strong>Rich Greenfield</strong> =
at LightShed Partners asked Zaz about the WBD sports strategy these days. H=
e replied
that his team is =E2=80=9Cdisciplined=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Copportunistic=
=E2=80=9D when it comes to the sports rights opportunities and that WBD is =
=E2=80=9Cmoney good=E2=80=9D on almost all of its current sports offerings:=
 =E2=80=9CWe don=E2=80=99t need any more sports anywhere in the world in or=
der to support our business.=E2=80=9D Gunnar added that =E2=80=9Cseveral hu=
ndred million=E2=80=9D dollars of expenses related to sports will be elimin=
ated in 2026, along with some associated ad revenue, of course. =E2=80=9CBu=
t this should certainly be a few hundred million dollar improvement in
2026 over 2025,=E2=80=9D he said.</p></div>
